Abortion is criminalized in Senegal for any woman under 21 years of age except in cases of rape, incest or threat to the life of the mother or fetus. See article on this report here.

Abortion is illegal in Somalia and punishment can be sentenced up to 15 years in prison and a fine. The situation is complicated by civil wars in different Somali States. It is less likely than in other East African Muslim-majority countries for health care to be provided at any point in pregnancy and when illegality results in there being no services, fewer women want abortion than in jurisdictions where abortion is near to being banned, or where abortion services exist as normal health care.

Abortion is illegal in Sudan. Abortion is only sanctioned with the permission of the Federal Minister of Justice in Sudan, but the process for obtaining this is extremely difficult and it is widely accepted that it is virtually impossible to obtain permission in practice.

Abortion is illegal in Uganda. Abortion is illegal in all circumstances. Any person who helps a woman obtain or perform an abortion, conspires to help another to have an abortion, or attempts to perform an abortion, may be imprisoned for up to five years (criminal procedure section 113).
